<dl id="n03094b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03094b">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03094b"> 94(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> (Adamnan / King Finaghta / the Festive <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n03094b"><li>FW 41.24 </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/lexb.htm#n03094b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/l39b.htm#n03094b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n03094b">MS BL 47472-141</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:059 <a name="b2d3" href="../../FF/fdra/bda.htm#b2d3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/b/bd3.htm#n03094b">Draft: I.2&sect;2.3</a>/3.3</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"> Sometimes even rich and nobly born scholars chose to <font color="green">[act as servants]</font> by way of discipline. A story is told of the schooldays of Adamnan &hellip; <font color="green">[Adamnan, making way for <mark>King Finaghta the Festive</mark> and his retinue, upset and broke a jar of milk he was carrying to the noble scholars he was serving. Not recognising the King, he complained and the amused King promised he would make good the damage and also see to Adamnan&apos;s future welfare. He later summoned Adamnan to his court as friend and spiritual adviser.]</font> <small> J.M. Flood, <a name="JMFI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JMFI"><cite title="source">Ireland: Its Saints and Scholars</cite></a> (n.d) 88</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
